{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_frenchbulldog_ver04/data/sn83045433/00280764115/1920073101/0095.xml":{"full_text":"ssgaSii WASHINGTON^HERALD\n?.NO. 5024. WASHINGTON, D. C., SATURDAY, JULY 31. 19%0. TWO CENTS\nINTACTRUSSIA\nAND OPEN DOOR\nURGED BY U.S.\nI Supreme Effort Launched\nTo Prevent Recognition\nOf Soviet.\nTO PROTECT FAR EAST\nWould Give Russia Time to\nStabilize Government\nUnhampered.\n<PiUle Ledjrr Serrlee.)\nThe United States, in the negotiations\nwhich have been launched with\nJapan, is playing world diplomacy\nfar wider sort, it was learned\nyesterday, than appears in the paraphrases\nof the Sakhalin, note made\npublic in Tokyo. The objective of\nthe United States, manifold in\nscope, includes the three followingmajor\nfactors:\nReaffirmation of the definite policy\noutlined and adhered to since\nthe armistice that there must be no\ndismemberment of Russia\nA supreme effort to prevent recognition.\non the part of any civilized\ngovernment, of Soviet Russia\nOpe* Door\" Demanded.\nAbsolute adherence to the policy\not the \"open door\" in the Far Kast.\nexpounded first by John Hay.\nIn diplomatic quarters here it is\nearned the United States has offered\nobjection that any of the allies\nin the world war should take\nadvantage of Russia's present plight\nr>r take any portion of her country\nas hostage.\nIn this stand United States\ntends to the theory, long expressed\nin official circles, that the ultimate\nregeneration of Russia fs a thing to\nbe expected and worRed for, and\nuntil such an awakening of the\nmass of the Russian people can\ntake place she is not to lose her\npreferential rights as an ally in the\nwar against Germany.\nFight Sovletinm.\nThe United States could. ofj\nouree. offer no objection to any\nrapproachement that Japan might be j\nable to effect with Russia after gov- i\nernment by the majority had been'\nduly constituted. This government,\nhowever, does fear the Bolshevists I\nmay be working for an alliance designed\nmerely to spread the Soviet\ndoctrines and in which the loss of\nterritory would be offset by the infiltration\nof the Bolshevist Jerm!\ninto new lands.\nSteps taken by Sapan indicate k\ndesire to dominate two large sections\nof the Far Kast. in China and\nSiberia, and it is the absolute belief\nof the United States that anything\nthat tends to close up any part ofj\nChinese or Russian territory is a|\ndirect violation of the \"open door\"!\npolicy.\nFOUR INDICTED i\nAS AUTOGANGj\nSandy Spring Grand Jury\nCharges Robbery of Bank\nAnd Murder.\nJohn W. Mitchell and \"Gunman\nJoe\" Thomas, recently arrested in\nNew York and' Philadelphia, re-I\nppectlvely. on suspicion of being I\namong auto kandiU who on April\n2? last robbed the Sandy Spring j\nbank and killed Director Francis\nM. Hallowed, were fftrmally charged i\nwith the crime by a grand Jury!\nat the Rockville Court House yes- I\nterday.\nTwo indictments were returned\nagainst each of the prisoners. One j\ncharges the men with the larceny j\nof S5.317. and the other with the j\nmurder of Director Hallowed. Indicted\nwith them were Clarence\nAdams. alias Joseph Kane, and John\nKelly, alias Frank Wilson, now in\nthe Baltimore City jail.\nState's Attorney Dawson prepared\nextrrdition papers on which\nThomas will be brought to Balti-\nmore from Philadelphia.\nA special session of the Circuit\nCourt for Montgomery County will I\nhe called at m early date to try I\nthe four men. It was declared yesterday.\nIt is believed a change, or\nvenue will be asked.\nSPRING TIM\nIT was a day in March. Never,\nnever begin a story this way\nwhen you write one. No opening\ncould possibly be worse. It is\nunimaginative, flat, dry and likely\nto consist of mere wind. But in\nthis instance it Is allowable. For\nthe following paragraph, which\nshould have Inaugurated the narrative.\nis too wildly extravagant\nand preposterous to be flaunted in\nthe face of the reader without\npreparation.\nSarah was crying over her bill\nof fare.\nThink of a New York girl shedding\ntears on the menu card!\nTo account for this you will be\nallowed to guess that the lobsters\ns\nCalifornia Leader\nVisits Washington\n^fiiii\nJ&: ^gj\n*1\nix'\nMRS. CHARLES LAN DO.\\\nUO.NOHOE,\nCalifornia political leader, now\nin Washington. After attending\nthe Cox notiflcaton ceremony\nin Dayton. Ohio, she will\norganize California women in\nthe Democratc forces\nBRITAIN FEARS\nSHIP DISASTER\nBrooke Slain in Dublin.\nGuards Irish Troop Movement\nwith Secrecy.\nLondon, July 3?.?Thr military\nand police are burning houara\nin the neighborhood of Pallaa.\nwhere Brig. Gen. I.ocaa. who enraped\ntoday, was imprisoned,\naccording to a dispatch from\nTlpperary.\n(By 1 nivernal Service.)\nLondon. July 30.?The British!\ngovernment is fearful that troop-'\nships bearing soldiers to Ireland!\nwill be sunk and for that reason is'\nshrouding movements in greatest'\nmystery. The fear of sinking was1\nvoiced at the Irish office today when j\ninquiry was made as to the number:\nof troops now en route to Ireland.\n\nFrank Brooke, chairman of the j\nDublin and Southeastern Railway,\nand reputed virtual \"head of the\nBritish government in Ireland in!\nthe absence of Viscount French, i\ni\nwas shot dead in Dublin etoday justj\nas he entered the board room of his,\nrailway for a directors' meeting.\nBrooke was standing talking to j\nhis general manager when three j\narmed men entered the room and!\ncommenced firing. Brooke was one j\nof the richest men in Ireland and\nwas the confidential adviser of Viscount\nFrench. I\n\"Motherhood of Nath\nSays IVoman Demc\nWho Foresees Age\nTrue feminine idealism will dom-\ninate the work of the brainy and\nable women politicians who from\nnow will figure largely in Amer-\nf?an politics, according to Mrs. j\nCharles Landon Donohoe, who rep-\nresented California at the San j\nFrancisco convention. Mrs. Dono- 1\nhoe is visiting Washington prelim-\nRacing Car Dives\nDown Precipice;\nDriver Escapes\n\ni Special to The Herald.)\nElkins. W. Va.. July 30.?While I\nracing a car against a passenger\ntrain from Elkins ttn Norton last'\nnight Ray Hupp, a re clerk, lost J\ncontrol of the wheel while round- j\ning a sharp curve and the car went\nover a 100-foot precipice.\nThe machine turned four or five j\nsomersaults in its wild fall. Hupp i\nwas thrown out at the first turn I\nand landed on a ledge of the bowlder.\nHe was severely cut about the i\nhead and face. The car was j\nsmashed into pieces.\nEA_LA CAR\nwere all out, or* that she had\nsworn off ce cream during Lent,\nor that she had ordered onions,\nor that she had just come from\na Hackett matinee. And then,\nall these theories being wrong,\nyou will please let the story proceed.\nThe gentleman who announced\nthat the world was an oystec\nwhich he with his sword would\nopen, made a larger hit than he\ndeserved. It is not difficult to\nopen an oyster with a sword. But\ndid you ever notice any one try\nto open the te'rrestriai bivallve\nwith a typewriter? Like to wait\nfor a dozen raw opened that way?\nSarah had managed to pry apart\nTEN MILLIONS\nOFFERED PONZI\nFOR BUSINESS\nSolvency Apparently Accepted?State\nProbe of\nMethods Continues.\nGOVERNMENT PROFITS\nBoston \"Postage Stamp\nWizard\" Makes $500,000\nIn Five-Day Run.\n<By Ualvermal Serviee.\nj Boston/July 30.?The question of I\nsolvency of Charles Ponzi, the\n1 \"postage stamp wizard\" of Pie i\nI Alley, who pays 50 per cent on in-;\nj vestments in forty-flve days, seemed j\nj to be definitely settled in the minds\n[of his clients today.\nAbare handful gathered, formed J\na short queue, were paid their,\nj money on presentation of their j\nI notes and left without demonstra- I\nj tion. Clerks said almost as many i\nof the notes paid today were matured\nas there were those of un- j\ni trusting investors.\nS1..VM.000 Paid Oat.\nFor five days the run on the lit-\njtle office in the alley behind the\n[City Hall had kept up. Ponzi's\nclerks estimate they have paid out j\nabout $1,500,000 during the time,\nand say they have more than twice\nthe amount necessary to liquidate\nthe claim of every customer on hand j\nin Boston.\nPonzi, personally, refused to dis- i\ncuss \"the offer hft is said to have\nreceived from a New York banker\nof $10.0*00.000 for his business, fur- J\nther than to say that he had not J\ni decided what action he would take.\nHe intimated he would hold a con- I\nference witl* the Wall Street flnan-j\nJ cier within the next few days to\ntalk over the matter.\n\"There are $30,000,000 to $40,000,|\n000 yet to be made out of this\nj thing.\" Ponzi repeated, \"but a man\nwill have td hurry to do it. There\nmust be no delay.\"\nGovernment Make* Profit.\nThe run of frightened investors.\nPonzi estimates, has meant more\nmoney in his pocket than if they\nhad let their notes mature. He\npoints out that nearly $1,000,000 he\npaid out was on incompleted notes\non which he paid no interest. At 50\nper cent, this has meant a saving of\n$500,000. he estimates, since most of j\nthe accounts were within a short\nperiod of maturity..\nFrom Washington the report1'\ncame today that the United States j\ngovernment has probably made al-j,\nmost as much out of the unequal\nforeign exchange as has Ponzi. This\nis due to the fact that conversion\nrates remained constant while for- l\neign exchange fluctuated violently.\nNew conversion rates go into effect\nAugust 15, however, which will un-I\ndoubtedly reduce, though not en-ji\ntirely eliminate, the government's!,\nprofits on foreign money orders.\nAttorney General Allen said this\nCONTINUED ON PAGE TWO.\nonto Rule Politics,\" I'\nicratic State Leader, j,\nof Feminine Idealism'\n\n11\ninary to attending the Cox notittcation\nceremony at Dayton, Ohio.\n-Women are needed In politics.\"\nsaid Mrs. Donohoe, \"but their entering\nthis field does not mean that\nthey wi,l sacrifice one iota of their\nwomanly idealism. On the con-I\ntrary. they will direct their energy\nalong Its natural lines and!\nbring to the wofld of politics a!\nnew. clean force Inimical to every-\nthing that savors of sharp practice\nand demanding that America\nattain the very highest measure I\npossible of civic righteousness, and\nthat humanity and kindliness run\nthrough the fabric of government.\n\"Along 'he?e lines lies woman's\nmission in the public life of the\nUnited States. Politics will not 1\nmake woman mannish, but women j\nwill make politics represent the\nmotherhood of the nation.\"\nMrs. Dono.'me was the guest ot\nhonor at the Women's Press Club\nluncheon yesterday and was entertained\nin the evening by Commissioner\nClara Sears Taylor, of the!\nRent Commission.\nShe will leave for Dayton on I\nMonday and tfrom there will pro- I\nceed directly to Cos Angeles, where\nshe will begin the organization of\nthe women of (The Bunset State un- I\nder the Cox banner.\nTE\nthe shells with her unhandy\nweapon far enough to nibble a\nwee bit at the cold and clammy\nworld within. She knew no more\nshorthand than if she had been\na graduate in stenography Just\nlet slip upon h? world by a business\ncollege. 80, not bring able\nto steaog. she could not enter\nthat bright galaxy of office talent.\nShe wa# a free-lance typewriter\nand canvassed for odd Jobs\nof CO pying.\nThe most fcrllliant and crowding\nfeat oil Sarah's battle with the\nworld the ?tal she made with\nSchulentMrg* (one Restaurant.\nThe re?t?ur*nt was next door to\nthe old red brick in which she\nv j\nTHEY SMILE BECAUSE IT'S FUN\nTO BE CLERKS IN WHITE HOUSE\nV Y^#^gpf -f (BfMMBy^\nJ *^^mmr-y. .^shW\nBHKi liiPw^''SiNiKH^^B\ni Tf\\? on^y women ever employed in the p*mi?;vn ^a; r\nrvw V hitl,Housc arc Miss Maude Roger, and Miss Linia?n\nS?r=^;S\nsSEI13F^^?^_\nfing/)/ Future for Business\nRevealed by Federal Review\nOf 13ankConditiojis inNation\n\"Th?re'liI,iI Ml i \"*\",7'1 orally been accompanied, by a de.\nmere is absolutely no justifica-1cline in deno?it? i.\n'\"\"'h:r.:',T-\"\"-: z-lzzu*z Z':T\nrtnanc.a, circ.es man/\"\"\"/ h\"h\nof the Unit