h of this world of profiteers and self-seekers. Come\nI with me to the beautiful Marquesas where everything is free for\nthe taking, and live the simple life under a tropical sun. Evening\nj dress is barred.\n\"There arc about 3,000 narives in the islands, and I would\ndescribe them as thorough gentlemen. For nourishment there is\nthe choice of fish, fruit, vegetables, eggs, poultry, pineapple and\nmangoes with copious draughts from the cocoanut groves.\n\"We will market our produce on the co-operative system and\nthe timber of the islands will provide our dwellings.\nThere are no salaried officials.\"\nThink of a New York g\nding tears on a men\nhall-roomed. One evening: after and proper heads from \"hors\nnner at Schulenberg's 40-cent. d'oeuvre\" to \"not responsible for\ne course table d'hote (served overcoats and umbrellas.\"\nbLe'han a\\ y?U thrOW the ftve Schulenberg became a naturalDails\nat the colored gentle- ized citizen on the spot Before\nwuk'v he*d> Sarah took awa> Sarah left him she had him wilwritten\"*\nthe b'\" ?f farC U W*S ,inS'y committed to an agreement.\nscriot n 1,^\" alm0,,t unreadab,e She was to furnish typewritten\nP neither English nor Ger- bills of fare for the twenty-one\nroan, and so arranged that if you tables in the restaurant a new\nr 7L,Z0t, fareful 5,0,1 be*an wlth bi|l 'or each day's dinner, and\nP k and r'ce Pudding and new ones for breakfast and lunch\nthe ?w *k'th \"?UP and thC da> ?f 8S ?ft,\"n a\" chanses occurred in\nthe food or as neatness required.\nSchllL.?**' d8y Sarah showed In return 'or this Schulenberg\nnberg a neat card on which was to send three meals per diem\ne menu was beautifully type- to Sarah's hall room by a waiter\nr ten with the viands tempting- ?an obsequious one If possible?\nmarshaled under their right and furnish her each kfternoon\nV\n1\nLA FOLLETTE IN\nCAMPAIGN. ON\nFOURTH TICKET\nWisconsin Senator Consents\ni To Run as Candidate of\n48 Committee.\nI\n34 STATES LINED UP\nNational Officer Discusses\nPresidential Possibility\nFrom Detroit Office.\n(By I a I re rum I Seniw.)\nDetroit, Mich, July 30?Senator\nRobert M LaFollette has consented\nto run for President on a ticket toj\nbe placed in the field by the Com-j\nmittee of Forty-eight, It was announced\ntonight b Howard F. Williams,\nnational vice chairman of the!\nForty-*elghters, who is here to take\ncharge of the campaign in Michigan, j\nWilliams said the ticket would ^e\nin the field in about thirty-four j\nj States in addition to Michigan.\nF?T*rfd hy Tkoauadi.\nThe Senator consented, Williams\nI said, after he had received thousands\nof telegrams urging him to j\nrun \"so millions of voters who are\ndisgusted with the old parties and 1\ndo not approve of political action on\nclass lines may not be disfranchised 1\nthis fall by having no candidate for!\nwhom they can vote.\nf \"The Senator/' Williams added,\n\"believes first that the failure of j\nthe forty-eighters and the laborites\nto unite in Chicago had spoiled the\nchances for establishment of a\npermanent Progressive party this\nyear, as much as he was willing to j\naid in its formation.\nC onvinced By Cirounawell.\n\"The nation-wide 'groundswell'\ntoward a nonclass Progressive party\nconvinced him. however, that it was\nhis duty to lead his support to the\nmovement: He believes with the i\nFirty-eighters that the so-called\nI Farmer Labor party represents i\nneither the farmers nor labor and\nwill only split the negligible class j\nvote that otherwise would have\ngone to Debs, whereasfthe new Liberal\nparty will get all the votes i\nwhich might go to Debs or the j\nLaborites merely as a protest.\"\nFRENCHPREP ARE ARMY I\ni EXPECTING RED REBUFF\nj Paris. July 30. Despite the\niostensibly sanguine attitude of the'\nj allied premiers, it was revealed this'\n'morning that military preparations1\nI in France apparently in conjunc- J\ntion with Great Britain are being\npushed with greatest vigor and\nsecrecy, proving the settled belief i\nof the French army chiefs that the\n1 Soviets will refuse a majority of\nthe conditions contained in the proposal\nof Premier Lloyd George from\nBoulogne.\nJrishGuerrillaWarM\nWest Front in 19\nIs Told by Bri\n\n(By I nivernal Service.)\nLondon, July 30.?The terrors of\nthe guerrilla warfare in Ireland are\nfar worse than the most vicious\noccurrences on the Western front.\nPremier Lloyd George was informed\nby one of the ablest generals in the\nBritish army, according to the\nUnionist deputation wh'ch queried\nj the prime minister on Irish affairs\ny< sterday.\n\"The Irish outbreak.\" the premier\nis quoted as saying, \"came\nwhen the organization behind the\nlaw in Ireland weakened the force\nRED BLOODED MEN\nWho follow the happenings\nin the world of athletics,\nfind the livest sport news\nand the best sporting page\nfeatures in\nThe Sports Section\nOf The Washington Herald.\nWatch the Nationals with\nJack Nye. and the horses\nwith Collyer.\nirl shedtu\ncard!\nwith a pencil draft of what Fate\nhad in store for Schulenberg's\ncustomers on the morrow.\n0 Mutual satisfaction resulted\nfrom the agreement. Schulenberg's\npatrons now knew what\nthe food they ate was called even\nif its nature sometimes pusxled\nthem. And Sarah had food during\na cold, dull winter, which was\nthe main thing with her.\nAnd then the almanac lied, and\nsaid that spring had come. Spring\ncomes when it comes. The frosen\nsnows of January still lay like\nadamant in the cross-town streets.\nThe hand-organs still pla>;ed \"In\nthe Good Old Summertime.\" with\ntheir December vivacity and ex*\nWould Fight Wars\nBy Blocking Food\n\nI\nArthur joskph balfoi'r,\nWho advocates use of a food\nblockade u a principal weapon\nJv >*MTue of nations. He is\nx the British representative on\nof nations council.\n\"We must have an economic\nblockade,\" Balfour has said.\nNo nation <*.oul3 long withstand\nsuch a vf-apon, nor do I\nthink that any civilized nation\nwould destroy itself b* inviting\nauch a penalty. The economic\nblockade would five the league\na power that would seldom be\ndenied.\"\nPALMER PLANS\nTO KEEP POST\nAnnounces Dissolution of^\nStaff Does Not Mean\nHis Resignation.\nPhiladelphia. July 30. Mitchell\nPalmer asserted today he has no\nintention of resigning as Attorney\nGeneral of the United States. Over!\nthe long-distance telephone from\nhis home in Stroudsburg. Pa.. Mr. i\nPalmer denied published rumors\nthat the gradual breaking up of his I\nanti-radical and anti-profiteering j\nstaffs forecast his own withdrawal j\nfrom the Wilson Cabinet.\nFrank Burke, assistant chief of i\nthe Bureau of Investigation of the J\ndepartment, has tendered his resignation.\neffective August 1. it was\nlearned in Wl^hington today. Mr.\nBurke will become assistant to\nChairman Benson, of the Shipping\nBoard. He has been prominent in\nthe investigation of radical activities.\nThe withdrawal of other high officials\nfrotn the Department of Justice\nis impending. C. B Ame.s assistant\nto the Attorney General, and\nWilliam J. Flynn. chief of the Bu- I\nreau of Investigation and head of\nthe anti-radical campaign. have I\nsignified their intention of resign- j\ning.\n(Public Udffr Service.i\nore Dreadful Than\n1 8, Lloyd George\ntish General on Scene\nessential to the preservation of law.\nThe government is strengthening\nthe forces, but hundreds of thousands\nof recruits are necessary, and\nthe military leaders should have\nthem to put down the conspiracy j\nof lawlessness I would like to see\nthe same assistance gi\\en to the'\ngovernment gaining recruits now as\nwas given during the war.\nUndoubtedly Bolshevist support\nand perhaps Bolshevist money is\nback of the movement, but is not\nthe whole movement The outbreak\nis the recurrence of an old\nfeud, but is the worst outbreak of\nthe entire feud.\"\n^e must not defer to extreme\nlabor leaders.\" he said, \"but it is\nvital to separate the extremists\nfrom the solid mass which is sensible.\nmoderate and sound. We must\nget these on our side.\"\nReplying to Member Ronald McNeill.\nthe premier said that he did\nnot intend anything beyond the present\nhome rule bill when he spoke\nof \"*ny self-government consistent\nwith the supremacy and the secury\nll1? United Kingdom.\"\n\na\npresslon. Men began to maka\nthirty-day notes to buy Easter\ndresses. Janitors shut off steam.\nAnd when these things happen,\none may know that the city is still\nin the clutches of winter.\nOne afternoon Sarah shivered\nin her elegant hall bedroom;\n\"house heated; scrupulously clean;\nconvenient; seen to be appreciated.\nShe had no work to do except\nSchulenberg's menu cards.\nSarah sat in her squeaky willow\nrocker, and looked out the window.\nThe calendar on the wall\nkept crying to her: \"Springtime\nIs here, Sarah springtime is\nhere, I tell yo.u l?oafc at rr. S?>rah.\nmy figures You gvt a\nWILSON SCORES\nMINERS IN PLEA\nAGAINST STRIKE\nTelegram Gtes Violation of\nAward and Pledge to\nGovernment.\nWARNS OF HARDSHIPS\nVitally Necessary Coal Production\nDemanded Before\nSteps for Relief.\ni By ralmal trniw.1\nPresident Wilson, 1n a telegram\naddressed to the nembtri of Lht\nUnited Mine Worker* of America\nyesterday took coolniice of the\nIllinois strike with a demand that\nthe vitally tiecessary mining of coa.\nbe resumed before he will ask the\nBituminous Coal Commission to\nconsider Inequalities.\nThe President's telegram pledged\nthe miners that in event of their\nreturn to work he will invite the\nscale committees of the operatonand\nminers to confer.\nSecretary's Viewpoint.\nThe President's action obviously\nguided by the views of Secretary\nof Labor Wilson. For two\ndsys the report of Secretary Wilson\nhad been In the President's\nhands.\nThe President let the miners know\nhis disapproval of the strike \"In\nviolation of the terms of the sward\nof the Bituminous Coal Commission\nand your agreement with the government\nHe pictured the result in\nhousehold suffering and interference\nwith industrial and agricultural activity.\nIt may now make temporary\ngains by taking advantage of the\ndire necessities of the balance of\nthe people through the v-iolatloa mt\nthose contracts, but what of the f?.\ntureT he asked \"How will It fc*\ntble to resist the claims of the operators\nin the future.\n??elaU See Tsailtj.\nYesterday afternoon D. B Wnti,\npresident of the National Coal Association.\nrepresenting two-thle4s\nof the operators of the country,\nand J* P A. Morrow, vloe jirrslflsil\nof the association, conferred wit*\nSecretary Tumulty.\nAt a conference of operators en\ncared in the export of bituminous\nccal. at the Hotel Washington yesterday\nmeasures to eliminate speculation\nin shipments of coal from the\nmines to tidewater points, either for\nexport or for trans-shipment to\nAmerican ports, were guarded\nsgslnst by appointment of a committee\nto formulate practical plana\ninvolving a severe limitation on the\nreconsignment of car*, for submission\nto railway executives and officials\nof the Intristate Commerce\nCommission.\nDivorce Asked\nBy Man Unaware\nOf His Wedding\n(Special to Herald.)\nTaurton. Maw.. July 30?Does an\nunconscious case of matrimony\ntake? It shouldn't. sa>s Joseph r\nSousa. of New Bedford, who in thu*\nafflicted.\nJoseph m a? maried when he didn't\nKnow it, he say*, but his wife aocn\nbrought him to a realisation of hitcondition.\nHe ha* asked annulment\nof his marriage to Miss Julia\n(Henry, of Ravnham. who wedded\nhim without his consent on July 24\nhe says.\nSour a understands very little\nEnglish. He became friendly with\nthe Henrys and a irequent visitor.\nOne day he came to Taunton with\nJulia and her father. They visited\nthe registry of probate and\nsome papers were filled out and\nmeaningless Knglish conversation\nindulged in. All this meant nothing\nto Joseph\nLater Julia told Joseph that ba\nwas her happy bridegroom\nOMAHA NEWSPAPERS\nADVANCE IN PRICE\nOmaha. July 30?Omaha's thres\ndaily newspapers, the Omaha Bee.\nWorld-Herald and Dally News, announced\ntoday an advance In pries\ncf all Sunday and weekday edition\nSunday papers will be sold at 1#\ncents and daily papers at cents,\ncompare With former prices of\ncents for Sunday and i cents dally.\nThe weekly price by carriers wlU\nbe advanced from IS to SO cents.\nThe change in price become effective\nSunday, August 1.\nBy 0. HENR Y\nneat figure yourself, Sarah a\nnice springtime figure why do\nyou look out the window so sadly?**\nSarah's room was at the back\nOf the house Looking out tl?\nwindow she could see the window*\nless rear brick wall of the bo*\nfactory on the next street. But\nthe wall was clearest crystal; and\nSarah was looking down a grassylane\nshaded with cherry trees and\nelma. and bordered with raspberry\nbushes and Cherokee rosea\nSprings real harbingers are too\nsubtle for the eye snd ear. Some\nmust^have the flowering crocua,\nco*nMEi? ox haoc ?k\\g.\\","height":"24652","width":"18740"}}
